After Albert I (W180) died 1279 his three sons ruled jointly the Braunschweig-WolfenbÃ¼ttel land to 1291 when an inheritance dispute provoked a division of the duchy. Henry I (W230) received the Grubenhagen area, Albert II (W240) received GÃ¶ttingen and William I (W250) received WolfenbÃ¼ttel.

Already in 1292 William died, and Albert took possession of WolfenbÃ¼ttel, while Henry withdrew to Grubenhagen.

