Braunschweig-LÃ¼neburg after Magnus of the Necklace

After the death of Magnus II in 1373 the War of Succession broke out and Dukes of Sachsen-Wittenberg claimed the LÃ¼neburg land against Magnus's widow and sons.

The claimers were Wenceslaus I of Sachsen-W. (W400) and his nephew Albert IV of Sachsen-W. (W410) (The Ascanins).

A reconciliation was agreed 1374, and the principality would alternatively be governed by the Ascanians and the Welfs beginning with the Ascanians. After Wenceslaus I and Albert IV had died, the ruling power would go to Magnus II's sons. An internal disagreement broke out at the Ascanians in 1388 and Wenceslaus prepared an army. However, he fell ill and died shortly thereafter.

A decisive battle 28/05 1388 was won by the Welf Henry (W245) and according to the agreement from 1373 the ruling power now went to the Welfs and Henry became the principal duke to his death 14/10 1416.

However, the agreement of 1374 was abolished and a new inheritance agreement was cocluded in 1389 and the Welfs were secured the pricipality of the LÃ¼neburg land.

